00098 /* Parses some input. Returns XML_STATUS_ERROR if a fatal error is
00099    detected.  The last call to XML_Parse must have isFinal true; len
00100    may be zero for this call (or any other).
00101 
00102    The XML_Status enum gives the possible return values for the
00103    XML_Parse and XML_ParseBuffer functions.  Though the return values
00104    for these functions has always been described as a Boolean value,
00105    the implementation, at least for the 1.95.x series, has always
00106    returned exactly one of these values.  The preprocessor #defines
00107    are included so this stanza can be added to code that still needs
00108    to support older versions of Expat 1.95.x:
00109 
00110    #ifndef XML_STATUS_OK
00111    #define XML_STATUS_OK    1
00112    #define XML_STATUS_ERROR 0
00113    #endif
00114 
00115    Otherwise, the #define hackery is quite ugly and would have been dropped.
00116 */
00117 enum XML_Status {
00118   XML_STATUS_ERROR = 0,
00119 #define XML_STATUS_ERROR XML_STATUS_ERROR
00120   XML_STATUS_OK = 1
00121 #define XML_STATUS_OK XML_STATUS_OK
00122 };

00124 /* If type == XML_CTYPE_EMPTY or XML_CTYPE_ANY, then quant will be
00125    XML_CQUANT_NONE, and the other fields will be zero or NULL.
00126    If type == XML_CTYPE_MIXED, then quant will be NONE or REP and
00127    numchildren will contain number of elements that may be mixed in
00128    and children point to an array of XML_Content cells that will be
00129    all of XML_CTYPE_NAME type with no quantification.
00130 
00131    If type == XML_CTYPE_NAME, then the name points to the name, and
00132    the numchildren field will be zero and children will be NULL. The
00133    quant fields indicates any quantifiers placed on the name.
00134 
00135    CHOICE and SEQ will have name NULL, the number of children in
00136    numchildren and children will point, recursively, to an array
00137    of XML_Content cells.
00138 
00139    The EMPTY, ANY, and MIXED types will only occur at top level.
00140 */

00215    names and attribute names that belong to a namespace will be
00216    expanded; unprefixed attribute names are never expanded; unprefixed
00217    element type names are expanded only if there is a default
00218    namespace. The expanded name is the concatenation of the namespace
00219    URI, the namespace separator character, and the local part of the
00220    name.  If the namespace separator is '\0' then the namespace URI

00396 /* This is called for a reference to an external parsed general
00397    entity.  The referenced entity is not automatically parsed.  The
00398    application can parse it immediately or later using
00399    XML_ExternalEntityParserCreate.
00400 
00401    The parser argument is the parser parsing the entity containing the
00402    reference; it can be passed as the parser argument to
00403    XML_ExternalEntityParserCreate.  The systemId argument is the
00404    system identifier as specified in the entity declaration; it will
00405    not be NULL.
00406 
00407    The base argument is the system identifier that should be used as
00408    the base for resolving systemId if systemId was relative; this is
00409    set by XML_SetBase; it may be NULL.
00410 
00411    The publicId argument is the public identifier as specified in the
00412    entity declaration, or NULL if none was specified; the whitespace
00413    in the public identifier will have been normalized as required by
00414    the XML spec.
00415 
00416    The context argument specifies the parsing context in the format
00417    expected by the context argument to XML_ExternalEntityParserCreate;
00418    context is valid only until the handler returns, so if the
00419    referenced entity is to be parsed later, it must be copied.
00420    context is NULL only when the entity is a parameter entity.
00421 
00422    The handler should return XML_STATUS_ERROR if processing should not
00423    continue because of a fatal error in the handling of the external
00424    entity.  In this case the calling parser will return an
00425    XML_ERROR_EXTERNAL_ENTITY_HANDLING error.
00426 
00427    Note that unlike other handlers the first argument is the parser,
00428    not userData.
00429 */
00430 typedef int (*XML_ExternalEntityRefHandler)(XML_Parser parser,
00431                                             const XML_Char *context,
00432                                             const XML_Char *base,
00433                                             const XML_Char *systemId,
00434                                             const XML_Char *publicId);

00450 /* This structure is filled in by the XML_UnknownEncodingHandler to
00451    provide information to the parser about encodings that are unknown
00452    to the parser.
00453 
00454    The map[b] member gives information about byte sequences whose
00455    first byte is b.
00456 
00457    If map[b] is c where c is >= 0, then b by itself encodes the
00458    Unicode scalar value c.
00459 
00460    If map[b] is -1, then the byte sequence is malformed.
00461 
00462    If map[b] is -n, where n >= 2, then b is the first byte of an
00463    n-byte sequence that encodes a single Unicode scalar value.
00464 
00465    The data member will be passed as the first argument to the convert
00466    function.
00467 
00468    The convert function is used to convert multibyte sequences; s will
00469    point to a n-byte sequence where map[(unsigned char)*s] == -n.  The
00470    convert function must return the Unicode scalar value represented
00471    by this byte sequence or -1 if the byte sequence is malformed.
00472 
00473    The convert function may be NULL if the encoding is a single-byte
00474    encoding, that is if map[b] >= -1 for all bytes b.
00475 
00476    When the parser is finished with the encoding, then if release is
00477    not NULL, it will call release passing it the data member; once
00478    release has been called, the convert function will not be called
00479    again.
00480 
00481    Expat places certain restrictions on the encodings that are supported
00482    using this mechanism.
00483 
00484    1. Every ASCII character that can appear in a well-formed XML document,
00485       other than the characters
00486 
00487       $@\^`{}~
00488 
00489       must be represented by a single byte, and that byte must be the
00490       same byte that represents that character in ASCII.
00491 
00492    2. No character may require more than 4 bytes to encode.
00493 
00494    3. All characters encoded must have Unicode scalar values <=
00495       0xFFFF, (i.e., characters that would be encoded by surrogates in
00496       UTF-16 are  not allowed).  Note that this restriction doesn't
00497       apply to the built-in support for UTF-8 and UTF-16.
00498 
00499    4. No Unicode character may be encoded by more than one distinct
00500       sequence of bytes.
00501 */
00502 typedef struct {
00503   int map[256];
00504   void *data;
00505   int (*convert)(void *data, const char *s);
00506   void (*release)(void *data);
00507 } XML_Encoding;

00524 typedef int (*XML_UnknownEncodingHandler)(void *encodingHandlerData,

00743 /* Creates an XML_Parser object that can parse an external general

00748    sequence of tokens separated by formfeeds (\f); a token consisting

00752    namespace.  This can be called at any point after the first call to
00753    an ExternalEntityRefHandler so longer as the parser has not yet

00755    safely be used in a separate thread.  The handlers and userData are
00756    initialized from the parser argument.  Returns NULL if out of memory.
00757    Otherwise returns a new XML_Parser object.
